<TEXT>
the board of directors of the associated press 
approved unanimously a 1989 general assessment increase of 44 
percent for newspaper and broadcast members 
the increase takes effect jan 15 1989 for aps 1463 
newspaper and 5700 broadcast members 
william j keating ap board chairman and chief executive 
officer of the detroit newspaper agency noted that the increase 
was below inflation estimates of 5 percent to 55 percent for next 
year 
the increase continues the recent trend of assessment 
adjustments less than the general rate of inflation he said 
tuesday 
keating said stringent cost controls and new revenues from 
nonmember sources enabled the board to restrict the increase to 
44 percent and still fund major service improvements now under way 
keating said the aps proposed operating and capital budgets 
were examined by the board on a detailed linebyline basis 
the budgets provide for expansion of aps news staff mostly in 
the united states to help meet the needs of aps 28 percent 
increase in newspaper membership over the past five years keating 
said 
the budgets also provide support for the new highspeed 
photostream and graphicsnet systems as well as for total 
replacement of editing systems in all domestic bureaus 
the general assessment increase will be combined with the fifth 
step of the phasein of the circulationbased newspaper formula for 
those not yet on card with the new formula which was adopted in 
1985 changes in circulation will also be reflected in the new 
assessment for each newspaper member 
each member will receive exact figures on the assessment change 
in october keating said 
</TEXT>
