<TEXT>
todays federal rules for pilot rest and duty hours come out of 
the era of the dc3 when propellerdriven airliners droned along 
at speeds less than 200 mph and took eight hours to fly from new 
york to miami 
revised in 1964 and again in 1985 many of the federal air 
regulations differ little from rules first issued in the 1930s 
crews for large airlines on domestic routes cant be scheduled 
to fly longer than eight hours between required rest periods they 
cant fly more than 30 hours in seven days 100 hours a month and 
1000 hours a year crews may exceed the eighthour limit if their 
scheduled flights are delayed by weather traffic or equipment 
problems 
commuter airline pilots may fly 34 hours in 7 days 120 hours in 
a month and 1200 a year 
crews must be given at least nine hours rest in a 24hour 
period however that can be cut to eight hours if the next rest 
period is increased by two to three hours based on an faa formula 
threemember international crews can fly up to 12 hours a day 
they must get 18 hours rest if they fly more than 24 hours in 72 
hours or 20 hours within 48 hours larger crews can fly longer 
twomember crews can fly only eight hours between rest periods 
however the rules dont speak to duty hours measured from the 
time a pilot reports to the airport usually an hour before first 
takeoff through the days schedule including sitting on the ground 
between flights to departure after the final flight such 
reckoning can stretch a crews time on the job to 16 hours 
west germany britain and the netherlands limit their pilots 
hours by calculating duty time the number of takeoffs and 
landings the time of day and the number of time zones crossed 
none of these factors is considered under us commercial 
regulations 
the latest faa rules are the result of socalled regulation by 
negotiation union and airline representatives met in 198384 
with faa officials and a mediator to work out minor changes in 
domestic rules 
these rules are often used by airlines and their unions as a 
baseline for schedules stricter than government guidelines 
our own rules go on beyond the far federal air 
regulations said george hof head of american airlines flight 
operations we find the far is a place to begin 
faa administrator t allan mcartor strongly denies federal 
regulations run second in safety to union contracts 
our standard is not the thinnest ice you can skate on he 
said 
yet in 1975 an faa investigation of a series of pan american 
crashes in the pacific raised questions about the adequacy of faa 
regulations 
dr stanley mohler then chief of the faas aeromedical 
applications division suggested us regulators look to the 
factors that the europeans use to set flying limits 
it was the feeling at the faa to leave it up to the unions to 
negotiate relative to their airlines specific type of flying 
said mohler now head of aerospace medicine at wright state 
university it seemed to make sense up until deregulation 
with deregulation airlines stretched into new markets added 
new routes and faced new competition efforts to cut costs and keep 
fares low put pressure on various parts of the industry including 
the pilots according to the airline pilots association the 
average pilot flies 13 percent more each month today than 10 years 
ago 
mcartor says he has an open mind to change the faa is 
supporting fatigue research being done by nasa on several airlines 
i dont know of any carrier that wont voluntarily do all they 
can to ensure efficiency in the cockpit he said but i dont 
believe we know all that we will know about this phenomenon as we 
understand it better the scheduling i think will reflect that 
</TEXT>
