<TEXT>
for the past two weeks the 
15000 people of this town have been living in flood waters 
they say they have received almost no help from the government 
although the town is only 25 miles east of dhaka the capital 
even in normal times banchharampur is isolated like thousands 
of other towns and villages in this country that is now 
threequarters submerged by overflowing rivers 
there are no roads connecting the town to the outside world the 
trip from dhaka takes five hours by motorboat across winding rivers 
and through inundated rice paddies 
most people in banchharampur are weavers or landless farmers who 
have not been able to work since the flood waters from the titash 
river reached their houses aug 29 
firoz who delivers goods from the market when it isnt flooded 
and his wife hana said they tried to get medical help for their 
7yearold daughter rahima who had a fever 
government medical workers came here once but the crowd was 
too big and they left before we could see them firoz said 
townspeople said eight people drowned or died of diarrhea or 
dysentery caused by drinking contaminated water he said his family 
had received 44 pounds of free rie from the government and had to 
borrow money from other villagers to buy more a grain seller named 
farid said he had only two baskets of lowquality rice to sell 
the government and foreign relief agencies are struggling to 
reach millions of marooned flood victims by helicopter and boat 
but with at least 65000 villages spread across 55000 square miles 
an area the size of wisconsin the task is slow 
on sunday fresh vegetables reached banchharampur by boat from 
unsubmerged fields 12 miles away but the prices had soared by as 
much as 175 percent since the floods began june 13 
sattar his wife alia and their three children normally eat 44 
pounds of rice a day since the flood the family has been getting 
by on 22 pounds or less of rice a day alia said she uncovered a 
tin cooking pot displaying an inch of rice in the bottom 
this is all we have left we have no more money she said 
speaking in bengali through an interpreter 
the family has purchased rice with sattars last earnings as a 
porter and money from the familys only salable item a chicken 
alia managed to save when they abandoned their straw house where 
the flood water has reached the roof 
we stayed in our house until the water got as high as 
saliha alia said drawing her oldest child close to her 
saliha wearing only a pair of cotton shorts and a jewelry stud 
in her nostril stood about three feet tall alia who like many 
bangladeshis doesnt have a family name said she did not know her 
daughters age but the girl appeared to be about 10 
alia said her family took refuge with 20 other people in one 
room of a hostel built for college students where the water was 18 
inches deep the families piled wooden benches on top of each other 
in two tiers creating a wobbly wooden platform above the water 
the highest path through the village is a foot under water some 
people are living in houses where women wade waistdeep in water to 
cook food on boards propped just above the water 
but life in the village went on the governmentrun bank was 
open although the few customers stood ankledeep in water at the 
deed registry office clerks sat on platforms above the water with 
a black goat tethered in their midst 
