<TEXT>
the defense department is pursuing the 
development of nuclear warheads that would penetrate the earth 
before detonating and which could be a more effective weapon 
against soviet underground command centers 
pentagon officials said monday that defense secretary frank c 
carlucci had authorized development of the socalled burrowing 
nukes that have been under study for years 
military scientists are convinced they would be far more 
powerful against underground bunkers than other nuclear devices 
that explode on the surface even if they dont pack the same 
explosive power 
the new weapon which is highly classified and the 
responsibility of the air force is formally known as an earth 
penetrator 
the energy department disclosed in june 1987 it had begun 
preliminary development work on the warhead needed for a burrowing 
missile because it expected the pentagon to request one 
according to a defense department spokeswoman and other pentagon 
sources that request now has been formally made the energy 
department will be expected to step up its work on warhead design 
while the air force pursues missile development and integration 
work 
spokeswoman jan bodyani said the pentagons defense acquisition 
board last month recommended approval of an air force statement on 
the need for the weapon and carlucci subsequently approved it 
she said the final authorization was dated aug 19 and 
approves this program as a new start she would not discuss 
program details such as funding and anticipated deployment 
schedules 
another pentagon official who insisted on anonymity said 
carlucci had directed the air force to provide cost estimates and 
predicted performance data for a more rudimentary version of the 
weapon that could be produced by modifying an existing missile or 
bomb 
there will almost certainly be an interim earth penetrator 
this official said but the authorization clears the way for the 
broadbased research needed to produce a brand new weapon 
the reagan administration recently has begun spotlighting soviet 
construction of underground bunkers saying it appears the russians 
are convinced they can protect their leaders while waging a nuclear 
war 
earlier this spring the defense department reported in its 
latest edition of the publication soviet military power that 
such construction had been under way for 40 years and the bunkers 
could accommodate thousands of people 
a burrowing warhead would not have to penetrate more than a few 
feet before posing an increased threat to a bunker but its not 
easy to develop a warhead that can withstand the shock of 
striking and burrowing through the ground one official said 
</TEXT>
