<TEXT>
the viewing area from which reporters and 
spectators have watched 25 space shuttle launches at the kennedy 
space center will be offlimits to most onlookers when shuttles 
start flying again because of safety concerns officials say 
the air force and nasa on monday announced the new precautions 
at the cape canaveral fla space facility citing studies that 
have shown that the danger to persons on the ground is much 
greater than was understood should an accident occur 
the restrictions cover the viewing area that overlooks launch 
complex 39 where space shuttle discovery is being prepared for 
space 
a press viewing area 35 miles from the launch pads has been 
used by media representatives since the shuttle program began 
invited guests including astronauts families watched from a 
nearby vip area and kennedy space center workers and their 
families also were able to watch from certain areas 
under the new plans most nearby areas will be cleared just 
before and during the launch details of the plans were to be 
explained at a briefing today at the washington headquarters of the 
national aeronautics and space administration 
the plan drew protests monday from rep bill nelson rfla who 
said at the kennedy space center that the house committee on 
science space and technology had argued against such a change in a 
letter sent friday to president reagan 
i dont think an iron curtain should be placed about the 
kennedy space center when were getting back into space said 
nelson a member of the committee and chairman of its subcommittee 
on space science and applications 
the press has been very much a part of the manned space flight 
program for 29 years and to arbitrarily say that some of that press 
has to be excluded is not right nelson said 
nasa officials said the new rules were developed after studies 
of the challenger explosion in january 1986 and the loss of an air 
force titan 34d the following april 
air force range safety officers monitor each launch and have the 
responsibility of blowing up any rocket that strays out of control 
during the challenger accident the solidfueled rocket booster 
engines broke away and were destroyed by the air force range safety 
officer a study of this accident and of the titan 34d loss gave 
new understanding of the dangers to people near the launch pad the 
announcement said 
under certain conditions a solid rocket booster released from 
the vehicle as a result of an accident would follow an unknown 
ballistic trajectory rather than begin to tumble on course as had 
been previously thought the announcement said 
also the statement said it was learned that if outofcontrol 
boosters had to be destroyed in flight the boosters fragmented 
into thousands of pieces and the explosive properties of unburned 
solid motor propellant were greater than originally determined in 
laboratory tests 
because of this new information the statement said nasa 
and the air force have determined that the prudent action is to 
minimize the population at the closein viewing areas 
accredited journalists will be able to work in the area except 
for the hours just before the launch and the launch itself the 
statement said 
during the prohibited period only media with an immediate 
need for the facilities at the press site will be allowed the 
rest it said will view the launch from a site on a causeway the 
alternate site will be equipped with a countdown clock audio 
commentary and video monitors 
about 3000 members of the media have requested accreditation 
for the first postchallenger launch that of discovery which is 
expected to occur in about two weeks the exact number that will be 
permitted at the press site has not been disclosed 
the letter to reagan from the congressional committee headed by 
rep robert a roe dnj said in part although we have no 
doubt that the new assessments leading to this proposal are well 
intended the calculation of such risks is highly uncertain 
it asked the president to intercede and permit continued access 
to traditional viewing areas 
</TEXT>
