cynthia koch 
weve had a lot of prehistoric archaelogists from all over the 
state coming over to look she said 
near the southeast part of the building archaeologists 
discovered part of an indian hearth from between 500 and 700 ad 
workers also uncovered a piece of a clay tobacco pipe carrying a 
design that dates it to between 1000 and 1500 ad 
the findings suggest the area was a popular settlement used over 
and over by succeeding generations because it sits on a bluff near 
the delaware river and between two streams the assunpink creek 
and pettys run 
when people started to think about it it made perfect 
sense said ms koch 
