<TEXT>
the white house is turning on some 
electionyear rose garden charm to celebrate president reagans 
signing of a bill that strengthens the governments power to combat 
housing discrimination 
some 100 congressional leaders cabinet officers and other 
administration 
officials were scheduled to gather today at the white house to 
witness the presidential signing ceremony 
the effort is seen as a boon to the white house aspirations of 
vice president george bush whose staff was described as helping 
forge a compromise on the measure 
but members of both parties however had rushed to become 
cosponsors of the measure after the president signaled his 
willingness to sign it into law 
the original fair housing law passed in 1968 after the 
assassination of martin luther king jr gave the federal 
government only a mediation role in settling housing disputes 
under the new law the secretary of housing and urban 
development is empowered to go to court to seek stiff fines against 
property owners accused of discrimination 
the bill received final congressional approval in early august 
before reagan left on his traditional threeweek summer vacation 
however the legislations transfer to the white house was delayed 
so that a signing ceremony could be held after reagans return to 
washington last week 
the measure gives the federal government its first significant 
powers to combate housing discrimination 
the handicapped and families with children under 18 would be 
protected for the first time from housing discrimination the 
current law covered discrimination against racial minorities and 
legislation signed into law in 1974 barred discrimination on the 
basis of sex 
sen arlen specter rpa a chief sponsor hailed the new 
legislation as giving the government a tough remedy against 
housing discrimination 
specter credited bushs staff with being very active in 
negotiating compromise language that helped bring the bill to the 
floor 
other primary sponsors of the bill included sen edward kennedy 
dmass and rep hamilton fish rny 
opponents of the measure such as sen steve symms ridaho 
had criticized the measure as unfair housing bill contending 
it intruded on property rights and increased costs due to 
accessibility requirements for the handicapped and disabled 
other major provisions of the bill include 
the secretary of housing and urban development would try to win 
a conciliation agreement after a complaint is filed if that effort 
fails the secretary or any party could take the case to an 
independent administrative law judge in hud or to us district 
court 
if the administrative judge finds that someone has engaged or 
is about to engage in a discriminatory practice he shall order 
appropriate relief which may include actual damages an injunction 
or civil penalties 
the maximum fines would be 10000 for a first violation 
25000 for a second violation in a fiveyear period and 50000 
for two or more violations within a sevenyear period 
new buildings with four or more units must be constructed to 
they are readily accessible to the handicapped doors must be wide 
enough to accommodate wheelchairs switches and outlets must be in 
accessible locations bathroom walls must be reinforced to allow 
later installation of grab bars this would apply to dwellings set 
for occupancy 30 months after the laws enactment 
children could be barred from housing intended for the elderly 
such housing is defined as a community where at least 80 percent of 
the dwellings are occupied by at least one person age 55 or older 
and significant facilities and services are provided or those 
occupied solely by people age 62 and older 
</TEXT>
