<TEXT>
thirty percent of highachieving 
teenagers said they have considered committing suicide and 45 
percent said they knew someone who had killed themself or had tried 
to a new survey found 
the 19th annual survey of high achievers conducted by polling 
teenagers listed in the directory whos who among american high 
school students found that 4 percent said they had tried to 
commit suicide 
since the survey began tracking attitudes toward suicide among 
high achievers four years ago the percentage who reported knowing 
a teenager who had attempted or committed suicide has grown from 
40 percent to 45 percent 
the percentage who reported having personally considered suicide 
has been relatively stable rising from 28 percent to 30 percent 
over the fouryear period while the percentage who report trying 
to commit suicide went from 3 percent to 4 percent the 
organization said 
the problem may be especially serious among black high 
achievers the organization said in a news release 
the survey found that 10 percent of the black highachievers 
polled this year said they had attempted suicide the survey 
results were based on responses from 2024 students 5 percent of 
whom were black the whos who organization said 
on other issues the new whos who survey found that drug use 
continues dropping among the nations brightest high school 
students with less than 1 percent reporting they smoke marijuana 
more than once a month thats down from 4 percent five years ago 
and 11 percent a decade ago 
alcohol use also is decreasing with 63 percent of the 
teenagers surveyed saying they never drink alcohol compared to 50 
percent in 1978 and 48 percent in 1983 
the news release did not contain a margin of error for the 
survey and whos who officials cautioned that it was not designed 
to be representative of all teens 
its important to note these statistics represent high 
