<TEXT>
a 1500yearold tomb uncovered on the 
northern coast of peru has yielded one of the richest collections 
of crafted gold and artifacts ever found in the americas the 
national geographic society announced today 
the tomb officials said was the burial place for a 
warriorpriest of the moche people a civilization that dominated 
the peruvian area from 100 ad to about the end of the 7th century 
this is the richest tomb ever excavated archaeologically in 
the western hemisphere according to christopher b donnan an 
expert on ancient peru 
walter alva director of the bruning archaeological museum in 
lambayeque peru said that the area near the village of sipan may 
be the burial site for a succession of highranking moche leaders 
and that other tombs with more treasure may be found 
i am sure that when we finish digging here we will know more 
about the life social and economic organization the metallurgical 
knowledge and religious practices of the moche alva was quoted 
as saying in an announcement released by the national geographic 
society 
officials said the moche peoples dominated the peruvian area 
prior to the time of the inca civilization the incas were the most 
powerful group in the area at the time of the spanish conquest in 
the 1530s 
the moche tomb was discovered after authorities learned in 
january 1987 that a number of remarkably fine gold and silver 
artifacts were being sold on the black market in peru police 
raided the home of a tomb robber and after a shoot out that killed 
one person recovered some of the treasures 
information gathered from the raid led to the sipan area and the 
tomb was found after careful excavation 
among the treasures found were a crown mask knives and jewelry 
of gold along with more than 1000 ceramic and copper artifacts 
in addition to the warriorpriest the tomb also contained the 
remains of two women and three other men all apparently part of a 
ceremonial entombment ritual 
excavation of the tomb was financed by the national geographic 
society under the auspices of the peruvian government 
</TEXT>
