<TEXT>
the defense department has ordered a cut in 
the required tour length for all military personnel stationed in 
panama as part of an effort to reduce the number of dependents in 
the troubled central american nation the pentagon said tuesday 
dan howard the departments chief spokesman said the policy 
change would reduce from 36 months to 30 months the required tour 
for servicemen accompanied by their families and drop from 24 
months to 15 months the tour for those deploying alone 
the latter reduction is considered the most important howard 
explained the department also is enforcing a change to its 
concurrent travel policy under which servicemen cannot bring 
their families to panama unless they have already secured housing 
on a military reservation 
since there is currently a waiting period of up to nine months 
for such housing the new tour length should encourage more 
soldiers just to go unaccompanied added maj kathy wood a 
pentagon spokeswoman 
panama is the home of the us southern command the 
organization responsible for all us military forces in central 
and south america about 10000 american servicemen are stationed 
permanently in panama and about 2200 others have been assigned 
there on a temporary basis since the spring to upgrade security at 
us bases 
according to wood the decision to reduce the tour lengths was 
made initially last week by the army gaining the approval of gen 
carl e vuono the chief of staff and army secretary john o 
marsh the defense department then reviewed the matter and ordered 
similar changes for the air force and navy which have much smaller 
contingents in panama 
over the past six months the pentagon has succeeded in reducing 
by 50 percent the number of military families living outside us 
bases in panama dropping the total still off base to about 1100 
the effort has taken on more momentum this summer because of what 
the united states describes as a deliberate campaign of harassing 
americans assigned to panama 
us officials in panama city said on aug 21 that american 
personnel had reported at least 240 incidents of harassment by 
panamanian authorities this year including attempts to extort 
bribes for traffic violations and the stoppage of mail 
the harassment comes at a time when the united states is 
continuing to press economic sanctions against panama in a bid to 
oust the countrys military leader gen manuel antonio noriega 
who has been indicted by two federal grand juries in florida on 
drugtrafficking charges 
