<TEXT>
the house passed legislation tuesday barring 
airlines aircraft manufacturers and other aviation companies from 
retaliating against employees who complain to the government about 
safety problems 
the measure prohibits employers from firing or taking other 
actions against workers who notify government agencies about what 
they believe are safety problems or who refuse to allow an 
aircraft to operate because they believe a hazardous condition 
exists 
the bill passed on a voice vote gained momentum this year 
after lawmakers heard from workers including pilots and other 
employees of eastern airlines who complained that pressure was 
placed by management on those who object to safety problems 
it is imperative employees feel they can come to the federal 
aviation administration or to congress with their safety concerns 
so the traveling public can be protected said rep glenn 
anderson dcalif chairman of the house public works and 
transportation committee 
the bills future is uncertain because there is no similar 
senate version there is a much broader senate measure that would 
protect all privatesector whistleblowers including aviation 
industry workers but that bill seems unlikely to pass this year 
the house bill would allow workers to appeal to the labor 
department if they believe they have lost their jobs or been 
punished because they complained about safety problems 
a party dissatisfied with the labor secretarys decision could 
appeal to an administrative law judge within the department and 
ultimately to the courts 
if a worker is found to have brought his complaint in bad faith 
the employee can be held liable for the companys legal fees up to 
5000 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

