this is one of a series of periodic reports 
compiled by associated press bureaus on how the us presidential 
election campaign is viewed abroad 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
here is a sampling of recent foreign press comment on the us 
presidential race between democrat michael dukakis and republican 
george bush 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
jan krauze writing from washington in le monde independent 
left of center of paris sept 12 dukakis is at the top 
dukakis is at the bottom bush is on the ground bush is in the 
sky for several months the two candidates for the american 
presidential election have been perched at the two ends of a 
seesaw rising and falling with the polls while the commentators 
flock alternatively in one direction or the other amplifying these 
movements to an extreme with a surprising unanimity 
there is really no reason for this game of teetertotter to 
stop the voters seem to be looking with a gloomy and sceptical eye 
at these two candidates scrambling to seduce them who both present 
themselves as representatives of the fair middle the main stream 
of opinion but who are scarcely successful in attracting that 
opinion two men who failing to convince by their own qualities 
apply themselves not without success to denouncing the faults of 
their rival and throwing low blows the seesaw is likely to stay in 
movement with more and more grating 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
arab editorialists reacted strongly to what bush and dukakis 
told a bnai brith assembly sept 7 in baltimore here is some of 
what arab newspaper editorials had to say 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the jordan times liberal progovernment of amman sept 10 
the performance of both us presidential contenders before 
bnai brith last wednesday was a misfortune for american 
statesmanship the two gentlemen acted more like gladiators than 
responsible leaders of their respective parties 
their willingness to outbid one another in support of israel 
and its bankrupt policies shocked all of us who watched it with 
dismay and disbelief mr bush assured the jewish constituency in 
the united states and through them israel that under his 
administration the united states would neither accept an effective 
united nations role in settling the arabisraeli conflict nor 
accept a palestinian state in the west bank 
his reasoning was unfortunate and untenable interpreting un 
involvement in the middle east peace process as tantamount to 
imposing a solution on israel is most regrettable calling any 
future palestinian state a threat to israel is also unwarranted 
how can a truncated and demilitarized state pose a threat to 
israel a country with nuclear capabilities 
by insinuating that such a state would also threaten the 
security and stability of jordan mr bush went beyond the realm of 
reality 
gov dukakis sadly attempted to outbid mr bush in support of 
israel for by asserting that washington will never accept a 
solution to the arabisraeli conflict no matter how just and 
legitimate if it is rejected by israel mr dukakis has 
permanently mortgaged his countrys national interests to israel 
 
it is sad to see wouldbe statesmen so lose sight of all 
longterm interests their own included in the shortterm hunt for 
votes 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
alrai progovernment of amman sept 10 statements by 
both us president candidates on the palestinian issue assures 
us of the absence of american truthfulness and sincerity toward the 
palestinian people in particular and the arab world in general 
</TEXT>
