<TEXT>
an appellate court heard arguments tuesday 
that the federal communications commission decision to abolish the 
fairness doctrine for broadcasters both hurt and advanced the cause 
of free speech 
the requirement that television and radio stations present 
opposing viewpoints on controversial questions was a prevalent 
deterrent to broadcasters to air public issues fcc general 
counsel diane s killory told a panel of the us circuit court of 
appeals here 
elimination of the doctrine would best further the publics 
interest in recieving robust debate on controversial issues she 
told the threejudge panel which is reviewing last years 40 fcc 
vote abolishing the fairness standard 
the fcc found that because there were so many sources of 
information the 38yearold fairness doctrine was no longer needed 
to ensure the dissemination of all points of view in the debate on 
a public issue she said 
enforcement of the fairness doctrine prompted many broadcasters 
to avoid controversial issues so they would not be required to air 
all sides to a question and the result was bland speech she said 
but andrew schwartzman executive director of the media access 
project accused the fcc of ignoring abundant evidence that many 
broadcast outlets had not presented alternate points of view on 
controversial subjects 
there was a blatant predisposition to reach this result the 
fcc has flipflopped he told circuit judges patricia wald 
kenneth starr and stephen williams 
why shouldnt an agency that now says were concerned about 
core first amendment values get credit for that starr asked 
its one thing for the fcc to say its sensitive to first 
amendment concerns schwartzman said but he accused the agency 
of conducting a onesided and narrow review 
if it found that the regulation had a chilling effect on free 
speech the commission is free to tinker with the adminstration 
of the fairness doctrine he said its very convenient outcome 
for the fcc to say there is a very chilling effect we have to 
throw out the whole thing 
but killory argued that stricter enforcment would require the 
fcc to get into the editorial judgment of broadcasters 
the fairness doctrine requires broadcast stations to present the 
opposing viewpoint on a controversial issue in the event that the 
other side had purchased advertising to promote its arguments 
the doctrines constitutionality was upheld by the supreme court 
in 1969 but in 1984 the high court said it would review that 
decision if presented with new evidence that enforcement was no 
longer necessary 
the next year the fcc concluded the doctrine no longer served 
the public interest but said it would continue its enforcement 
because of uncertainty over whetherit was legally binding 
in 1986 the federal appeals court here found that the fairness 
doctrine was not codified as part of the 1959 communications act 
meredith corp then challenged the constitutionality of the 
fairness doctrine after the fcc found that a station it owned in 
syracuse ny had filed to present opposing views about the 
construction of a nuclear power plant 
the appeals court ordered the fcc to consider merediths 
constitutional challenge a review that resulted in the aug 4 
1987 vote to abolish the doctrine 
floyd abrams a prominent first amendment lawyer who represents 
meredith urged the panel to defer to oldfashioned commission 
expertise which found that the public is receiving information 
not because of the fairness doctrine but in spite of the fairness 
doctrine 
communications attorney timothy dyk predicted the case will 
turn on a constitutional issue i think this is a case for the 
supreme court 
organizations supporting the cc included the national 
association of broadcasters the reporters committee for the 
freedom of the press and the american newspaper publishers 
association 
</TEXT>
