<TEXT>
in pennsylvania where the seriousness of 
radon contamination first came to light when a man set off 
radiation alarms at a nuclear plant the state is moving to 
regulate companies that test homes for the deadly gas 
the steps are the outgrowth of nearly four years experience with 
radon an odorless colorless gas the environmental protection 
agency has now linked to 20000 lung cancer deaths a year 
nationwide the epa said monday every home in the country should be 
tested for radon because contamination is wider spread than 
previously believed 
radon is a radioactive gas trace amounts of which are produced 
in the decay of uranium in soil and rocks the gas is present in 
the outdoors normally at about 05 percent of the epas 4 picocurie 
action level homes tend to concentrate radon indoors 
radon kills people by leaving its radioactive decay products in 
the lungs irradiating the tissues for a lifetime 
pennsylvania will require companies testing for the gas to pass 
a stateapproved course in radon detection demonstrate at least a 
year of professional experience and agree to provide radontesting 
data to the government said jason j gaertner a state department 
of environmental resources official 
after sept 21 it will be illegal to provide radon services 
in the state unless they are certified he said tuesday 
its simply a health issue which needs to be investigated 
house by house gaertner said the problem levels are 
sprodadic but in being sporadic theyre spread across the entire 
country there arent really bad areas there are problem homes 
gaertner who works in the ders bureau of radiation protection 
said his office received a tremendous number of calls tuesday 
because of the epa report 
what we are really telling them is the same message we have 
been giving the public for a year now gaertner said that 
message based on der data from the past is that problem homes can 
occur anywhere in the state but most people after testing dont 
have a problem 
in neighboring west virginia the state health department said 
it had received more than 50 calls by midday tuesday from 
residents concerned about the effects of radon gas 
what the people are mainly concerned about is how they can get 
the radon kits to have their homes tested said rod kovack a 
radiological technician for the health department weve been 
furnishing them with a list of places where they can obtain the 
kits and along with that list weve sent a couple of pamphlets 
that the epa has put out for concerned homeowners 
the pennsylvania department plans to publish guidelines for 
contractors and homeowners on specific remediation techniques for 
homes with unacceptable radon levels gaertner said a companion 
booklet will offer tips on selecting contractors along with a list 
of statecertified contractors he said 
this will help the public in that the industry will be 
regulated he said we havent seen severe problems but you 
want to make sure problems dont occur that the firms have proper 
training and that they are following the proper methods for 
remediation 
of the 429 pennsylvania homes tested in the national survey 
released monday 37 percent had more than 4 picocuries of 
radioactivity per liter of air the level used by the epa as the 
trigger for more sophisticated tests that determine if remediation 
is needed the highest level was 114 in perry county 
those readings contrast to levels in the thousands of picocuries 
found previously in the uraniumrich reading prong geological 
formation of eastern pennsylvania northern new jersey and new 
york gaertner said 
those earlier findings were accurate but rare he said 
what it did was present a distorted picture of the radon 
situation he said the highest reading we have encountered 
outside the reading prong is no more than 800 and now we do a 
statistically random study and the highest reading is 114 
on dec 14 1984 stanley watras a field engineer for a 
subcontractor building philadelphia electric cos limerick nuclear 
plant tripped radiation alarms as he went to work 
investigators discovered his home atop the reading prong had 
radon levels 675 times the acceptable state guidelines he and his 
family were evacuated 
the discovery awoke scientists and officials to the severity of 
radon contamination in some areas and led to the creation of the 
radiation bureau in gilbertsville about a two miles from watras 
home 
