<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency on tuesday 
issued a 370page set of regulations that requires almost all 
owners of underground tanks including the corner gasoline station 
to test and protect their tanks fix leaks and clean up spills 
one set of requirements applies to all tanks installed after 
december of this year another set gradually applies to the nearly 
2 million existing tanks 97 percent of them holding gasoline or 
other petroleum products and makes them generally meet the new 
tank standards in december 1998 
the first requirement to bite is that existing tanks more than 
25 years old must have leak detection systems which may be 
inventory checks and annual tightness tests installed in the 
coming year with the requirement applying to the youngest tanks in 
1993 corrosion protection systems and spill and overfilling 
prevention devices would be required only in 1998 
about 80 percent of the tanks in use are steel tanks without 
protection against rust epa says its surveys show that anywhere 
from 10 percent to 30 percent of the 750000 tank locations have 
or have had significant leaks 
only about 5 percent of existing tanks have leak detection 
systems 
the regulations four years in the drafting require 
doublewalled tanks or similar doublebarrier protection only for 
some 60000 chemical tanks and one environmental group immediately 
criticized the agency for the omission 
failure to require double barriers for petroleum product tanks 
means epa is leaving the us supply of drinking water vulnerable 
to petroleum contamination said staff scientists lois epstein of 
the environmental defense fund 
the regulations are designed to minimize their impact on the 
regulated community not to protect the environment and the public 
from the hzards of petroleum contamination she said 
but j winston porter assistant epa administrator with 
jurisdiction over the tank program said that secondary 
containment is quite expensive and would add unspecified billions 
to the cost of the final regulations 
one of his staff david obrien said a doublebarrier 
requirement would add 80000 to the cost of a new threetank 
service station and existing stations would have to rip out all 
their tanks if the requirement were imposed on existing 
installations 
such a station might have to spend 3000 to 8000 on a leak 
detection system and 10000 to 48000 on an electrical 
rustprevention system epa estimated 
as it stands the agency estimated that tank owners will have to 
spend the equivalent of 54 billion in todays dollars but the 
owners and society will reap 73 billion worth of benefits in 
reduced damage inventory losses and cleanup costs it did not 
present an estimate of the extra costs and benefits associated with 
double barriers nor did it estimate health benefits from less 
contamination of groundwater 
whether youre mom and pop or exxon it doesnt make a lot of 
sense to keep a leaking gasoline tank in the ground the liability 
is enormous porter said 
about a dozen states already have tank regulations of their own 
in place and part of tuesdays regulatory package was the 
announcement of procedures by which states can win approval of 
those programs from epa 
a state does not have to have a program at all which would 
leave epa to enforce the new regulations porter said the agency at 
this point had made no provision for operating tank programs and 
we hope very few states will opt out 
still to come in about six weeks are regulations prescribing 
financial responsibilities of tank owners epa administers a 500 
million fund to help pay for cleanups 
the regulations exempt septic tanks tanks of 1100 gallons or 
less storing fuel for farm or noncommercial use home heating oil 
tanks and tanks on basement floors which are considered 
aboveground tanks 
the regulations take effect 90 days from publication expected 
soon in the federal register 
</TEXT>
