<TEXT>
the soviet union has bought an additional 
350000 metric tons of us corn for delivery during the coming 
year the agriculture department said tuesday 
the sale brought total corn sold to the soviets in the last two 
weeks for the 198889 delivery year that started sept 1 to more 
than 295 million tons 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 394 bushels 
of corn or 367 bushels of wheat or soybeans the 350000 tons of 
corn would be about 138 million bushels 
corn prices have been averaging about 273 per bushel at the 
farm level according to usda estimates meaning that the latest 
sale could have a farm value of around 38 million 
as with the other recent sales no indication was given whether 
the new sales of corn to the soviets would count under the current 
longterm grain supply agreement between the two countries or be 
carried forward separately in case a new pact is forthcoming 
the current fiveyear pact is set to expire sept 30 and 
negotiators are trying to work out a new one or at least an 
extension of the current agreement to take effect on oct 1 
according to the agreement the annual purchases are supposed to 
include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn the 
soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as 
wheat corn or soybeans with every ton of beans counting as two 
tons of grain up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain 
equivalent 
prior to sales announced since sept 1 the soviet union had 
purchased 905 million tons of wheat and 517 million tons of corn 
for delivery in the fifth year of the agreement plus 830000 tons 
of soybeans and 13 million tons of soybean meal 
