<DOCNO> AP880913-0169 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
an agriculture department proposal to allow up 
to 10 percent salvaged meat and tiny bone chips in hot dogs without 
telling consumers about it on product labels was made over the 
objections of a white house regulatory aide documents disclosed 
tuesday 
jay plager administrator of information and regulatory affairs 
in the office of management and budget told usda in a letter aug 
19 that the proposed rule change does not appear to be consistent 
with several of the administrations basic regulatory principles 
nor does it appear that the potential benefits to society of 
this regulation outweigh the potential cost to society plager 
added 
christopher hicks the usdas general counsel replied that 
department officials do not agree with the conclusions set 
forth by plager 
there are compelling reasons for proposing this rule 
including the fact that it may produce benefits to society that 
outweigh societal costs hicks told plager in a sept 6 letter 
copies of the letters by plager and hicks were provided to the 
associated press 
advocates of the rule change contend that consumers wont buy 
products containing the salvaged material if labels inform them 
about it 
the proposal which began a 60day rulemaking procedure sept 9 
was announced monday by the departments food safety and inspection 
service 
it involves the use of mechanically separated meat or msm 
although current regulations describe it as mss to acknowledge 
the species of animal involved thus salvaged meat from a hog 
would be mechanically separated pork or msp 
according to the plan which will be open for public comment 
until nov 8 processors would be able to use mss to comprise up 
to 10 percent of the meat in franks bologna luncheon meats 
sausage and similar products without stating so on product labels 
however the label would have to indicate the percentage of the 
recommended daily allowance of calcium that the product contained 
calcium is a primary ingredient of bone tissue 
regulations limit the salvaged product to no more than 075 
percent calcium but bones are about onefourth calcium so that 
would translate into a maximum of about 3 percent bone 
the american meat institute a private association that 
represents meat packers and processors said in a statement that 
the use of calcium on labels would be a more meaningful and 
useful term to consumers than mss particularly to those who 
have a calcium deficiency and to a few who are allergic to calcium 
and should be warned away from such products 
there is no wholesomeness or safety issue involved in the 
mss proposal the institute said in the brief statement citing 
the departments own description of the product as safe and 
wholesome as the species from which it is derived 
but plager said the assertion that consumers would avoid 
products labeled as containing mss had not been documented in the 
proposed rule change 
furthermore if one accepts the assertion that some consumers 
would be reluctant to purchase a product that they know to contain 
mss why should this information be omitted from the label he 
said would its omission in other words be inconsistent with 
the fsis food safety and inspection service obligation to prevent 
labels that are false or misleading and hence contrary to fsis 
statutory mission to protect the public from misbranded items 
plager said that in seeking ways to carry out less burdensome 
food safety regulations we must also provide consumers with 
more rather than less information about food products so that 
they may reach informed market decisions 
under current regulations mss can comprise up to 20 percent 
of the meat portion of these products but the labels must state 
that the products contain mss 
the department said that under the proposed rule change which 
was sought by a group of meat processors and supported by the trade 
mss would not have to be listed in the ingredients statement 
on the label as long as it does not exceed 10 percent of the meat 
portion of the finished product 
when animals are slaughtered most of the red meat is cut or 
scraped from bones by hand but a lot of edible tissue clings to 
the bones and gristle particularly in neck bones ribs joints and 
other hardtoscrape places 
the bones and the attached meat remnants are put through a 
grinder and forced through fine sieves although most of the bones 
are strained out the resulting mixture still contains bits of bone 
about the size of ground pepper 
according to the meat processors who asked usda for the rule 
change no company at present is commercially producing mss for 
consumer products because of unwarranted negative connotations 
