<TEXT>
two national polls tuesday found george bush 
pulling past michael dukakis in the presidential race and they 
indicated that bush has scored points by pressing the pledge of 
allegiance as an issue 
bush led by eight points in both national surveys 4739 percent 
in a cbs newsnew york times poll and 4941 percent in a gallup 
poll the gallup poll found dukakis suffering his highest negative 
rating of the race 
two polls released monday showed a closer race but two surveys 
last week found bush leading by six and eight points respectively 
moreover the new polls found support for bush on underlying issues 
he has been pressing 
on defense 28 percent of the probable voters in the cbstimes 
poll said bush would make the nation stronger and only 4 percent 
said he would make it weaker by contrast 39 percent said dukakis 
would make us defenses weaker and just 13 percent said he would 
make the nation stronger the rest in both cases said defenses 
would remain unchanged 
in another measure gallup found that 68 percent of the 
registered voters it interviewed had heard of the pledge of 
allegiance issue and by a 21 margin they had a less favorable 
view of dukakis because of it 
bush in what has become a repeated refrain has criticized 
dukakis for vetoing legislation in massachusetts requiring teachers 
to lead classes in the pledge dukakis said he acted on the basis 
of a court opinion that the law was unconstitutional and he 
accused bush of impugning his patriotism 
but 70 percent in the cbstimes poll said teachers should be 
required to lead pupils in the pledge and half of that group said 
it should be mandated even if the courts ruled the requirement 
unconstitutional 
bush also has been stressing environmental issues traditionally 
a strong suit for democrats and the cbstimes poll found him 
ranked nearly evenly with dukakis on protecting the environment 
the cbstimes poll even found backing for bush on an issue 
dukakis had sought to make his own competence fiftyone percent 
said bush would be more competent at managing the federal 
government to 32 percent for dukakis 
overall the gallup survey found 40 percent expressing an 
unfavorable view of dukakis up from 32 percent three weeks ago and 
the highest all year for dukakis in gallups poll dukakis was 
rated favorably by more voters 53 percent but bush bettered him 
in both ratings with 59 percent favorable and 35 percent 
unfavorable 
dukakis confidence rating suffered in the cbstimes poll but 
in that measure bushs score worsened as well fiftynine percent 
said they would be uneasy with dukakis in an international crisis 
up from 53 percent just after the republican convention last month 
fewer 47 percent said they would be uneasy with bush in a 
crisis but that was up 10 points from the postconvention poll 
also 45 percent said they would be confident with bush down from 
51 percent for dukakis 28 percent expressed confidence little 
changed from 29 percent 
dukakis continued to lead bush on one other key issue 
fortyseven percent said the democrat would do more to help the 
middle class while 33 percent picked bush 
finally bush encountered a low rating on his choice of sen dan 
quayle of indiana as his running mate fiftyeight percent said 
they would be worried about quayle stepping in as president if 
something happened to bush and just 32 percent said quayle was 
qualified to serve as president 
the cbstimes poll was conducted among 1043 probably voters 
from thursday through sunday and had a margin of error of plus or 
minus 3 percentage points the gallup poll was done friday through 
sunday among 1003 registered voters and was given a fourpoint 
margin of error 
 
