investigators from the national transportation 
safety board talked with the captain of delta flight 1141 for the 
first time tuesday afternoon but gleaned no information that could 
pinpoint the cause of the aug 31 crash a board member said 
he does not know why this plane crashed said lee dickinson 
jr who summarized the ntsbs interview with delta capt larry 
davis in a telephone interview from washington dc 
davis who spent nearly two hours talking with investigators 
had been at parkland memorial hospital since his boeing 727 crashed 
as it took off from dallasfort worth international airport 
killing 14 
davis one of 94 survivors was discharged from the hospital 
following the ntsb interview wearing a back brace and with his 
mouth wired shut he left the hospital with his wife and delta 
officials a hospital spokeswoman said 
dickinson said the ntsb hadnt expected the interview with 
captain to yield a clue that might solve the puzzling crash 
although investigators had been awaiting permission to talk to 
davis davis physician had barred investigators from interviewing 
davis earlier 
davis told investigators that the flight from jackson miss to 
dallas had been uneventful and that everything seemed normal again 
as he waited on the taxiway to leave for salt lake city 
he recalled shutting down the right engine to save fuel as the 
plane waited on the runway then restarting it dickinson said 
but as the boeing 727 climbed into the air davis heard two 
loud bangs or explosions davis did not recall any warning 
beforehand to indicate something was amiss 
he previously experienced compressor stalls but nothing like 
this dickinson said 
davis told investigators he went to full power and simply 
tried to keep the airplane in the air but he doesnt recall 
looking down at his instrument panel to see if there were any 
warning signals activated 
investigators had hoped davis might be able to tell them if the 
planes wing flaps had been set correctly but he could only tell 
them that he remembered they were approved in a preflight checklist 
one of the inconsistencies the ntsb had been trying to clear up 
has been the fact the cockpit recording indicated the flaps were in 
a normal takeoff position for a boeing 727 
but wreckage from the plane showed the flaps to be in a 
retracted or improper position 
he said he does not remember anything in relation to the flap 
handle dickinson said 
