<TEXT>
a severe thunderstorm may have triggered a 
rock slide that sheared off the front of a greyhound bus killing 
five people and injuring 14 police said tuesday 
the accident occurred late monday as the driver and 20 
passengers drove through a mountainous strip of new mexico highway 
68 above the rainswollen rio grande about 50 miles north of santa 
fe the bus was en route to el paso texas from denver via 
albuquerque 
a boulder the size of a cars front end tumbled from the 
mountain as the bus approached striking it broadside and 
apparently killing the driver instantly police said 
it sheared the front end of the bus off said state police 
officer harold zuni 
witnesses said that after the boulder hit the bus crashed into 
several large rocks but remained upright the rocks probably 
prevented the bus from careening off a steep embankment and 
plummeting into the rio grande said the rev andrew mccomb a 
dixon fire department volunteer 
all we heard were screams said david fuller a mormon 
missionary from toronto traveling with another missionary sean k 
jones people were thrown out of the bus when we hit these rocks 
here 
the driver was identified as gaylon greer parks 39 of denver 
george gravley a spokesman for greyhound in dallas said parks had 
worked for the bus company exactly seven years on monday 
the dead were identified as peedjk akkandi sridnaran 59 
bombay india esther grimes 41 who was believed to be en route 
with her family to a new home in arizona from denver a 64yearold 
man from tokyo whose name was not being immediately released and 
a woman about 18 years old who carried no identification and is 
believed to be a mexican national 
authorities still were trying to identify the toddler belonging 
to the unidentified woman who was killed the child estimated to 
be 18 months to 2 years old was in the espanola hospital in stable 
condition and will be placed in the states custody if relatives 
cant be found officials said 
four of the 14 injured were hospitalized in either stable or 
satisfactory condition ten people were treated and released 
