<TEXT>
retired air force gen lauris norstad the 
first airman to serve as commander of nato forces in western 
europe is dead at the age of 81 
norstad died monday at tucson medical center officials at the 
hospital said the cause of death was not released 
norstad was a resident of tubac 60 miles south of tucson since 
1963 
promoted to brigadier general in 1943 one day after his 36th 
birthday norstad was involved in planning for the allied invasion 
of north africa he personally went ashore with the assault forces 
earning a silver star for gallantry 
gen dwight eisenhower then army chief of staff appointed 
norstad director of plans and operations after the war later when 
eisenhower was head of the north atlantic treaty organization he 
made norstad his leading air commander 
norstad was promoted to fourstar general in 1952 in 1956 he 
was appointed supreme commander of allied forces in western europe 
becoming the first airman to head the 15nation nato forces 
norstad graduated from the us military academy at west point 
in 1930 he transferred from the cavalry to the air corps in 1931 
norstad was named president of owenscorning fiberglas 
international after he retired from the military 
he is survived by his wife isabelle jenkins norstad and a 
daughter kristin jaffe of atlanta 
a memorial service will be held friday at the davismonthan air 
force base chapel burial will be sept 21 at arlington national 
cemetery 
</TEXT>
