kroger co said today it was exploring a 377 
billion defensive restructuring that would plunge the supermarket 
giant into debt and force it to sell assets after the haft family 
well known for hostile takeover attempts won federal clearance to 
acquire a chunk of the company 
the nations largest grocery chain which operates more than 
1300 supermarkets 900 convenience stores and other operations in 
29 states said in a statement that the possible restructuring was 
prompted partly by the high level of takeover and restructuring 
activity involving supermarket companies 
the statement also mentioned a federal trade commission ruling 
friday that allows the hafts a marylandbased clan of corporate 
takeover strategists who have unsuccessfully chased other 
supermarket chains but made huge profits in the process to acquire 
at least 15 million worth of kroger stock 
kroger said the restructuring would involve substantial but 
unspecified bank loans pay shareholders 48 in cash and securities 
per share and allow them to keep their stock kroger has about 
7857 million shares outstanding 
the substantial debt would be repaid from cash flow from 
operations disposition of noncore and underproductive assets 
significant reduction in capital expenditures and reduced 
expenses lyle everingham chairman and chief executive officer 
of the cincinnatibased company said in the statement the ftc 
ruling was the first official sign of the hafts interest in 
kroger but the commissions statement did not say how much kroger 
stock the hafts want to buy representatives for the hafts declined 
to comment 
krogers stock has traded heavily over the past five months 
partly because of rumors that the hafts and other potential 
acquirers were interested in the company 
news of the commissions decision started circulating friday 
sending krogers stock up 125 in heavy trading to close at 38 a 
share on monday the companys stock closed up another 150 at 
3950 also on heavy trading 
one analyst predicted that the hafts would likely break up 
kroger if they purchased it 
its almost certain that theyll start dismantling the company 
and selling off its assets said gary m giblen vice president 
at rotanmosle a houstonbased subsidiary of the investment firm 
of painewebber inc 
but giblen also said that robert haft and his father herbert 
who operate the dart group of landover md may be serious about 
running a grocery company they demonstrated that earlier this 
spring when they bought a small washington dc grocery chain 
instead of selling it off for the cash the hafts are using the 
company to learn how to manage a grocery firm giblen said 
the hafts have failed in their efforts to buy such companies as 
safeway supermarkets general and stop amp shop but have made 
profits in selling stock shares back to those companies 
