<DOCNO> AP880913-0251 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
after learning from japan about modern 
furnaces enlightened labor relations and customer service 
american steelmakers are once again looking across the pacific 
ocean this time for a steel process that may help protect us 
warships at sea and tanks on land 
highstrength lowalloy steel plate easier to weld less 
dependent on hardtoget alloying elements and potentially cheaper 
to make is the latest fruit of the japanese industrial system 
its the wave of the future said charles null head of the 
metals branch of the us navys sea systems command 
american steelmakers lag japan by 10 to 15 years in the 
computercontrolled processing needed to make the supertough 
steel but the navy is anxious to catch up 
the navy wants to build ships out of worldclass steel they 
want the best that money can buy and theyre willing to pay for 
it said harry i mchenry a steel specialist for the national 
institute of standards and technology formerly the national bureau 
of standards 
but right now the american steel plate producers dont have 
all the technical tools available to them mchenry said in a 
telephone interview from his boulder colo office 
besides the navys support the army is interested in the new 
plate for its armored vehicles the material has applications in 
commercial shipping as well 
the defense department hopes to win its request for 55 million 
in the 1989 defense budget to send american steel to japan for 
processing and to bring it back for testing if the plate meets 
specifications and congress appropriates more money the department 
would negotiate with domestic steel companies for one of them to 
upgrade a plate mill with the new technology in exchange for 
guaranteed sales 
were very excited about this project i think it has a great 
deal of potential for the us steel industry said michael 
corridore a pentagon industrial specialist who heads the program 
mchenry said the reasons american steelmakers lag the japanese 
in this area are intertwined with the forces that helped undermine 
americas postwar industrial power japan steelmakers invested 
early on in research that led to computerized processing the key 
to more precise manipulating of steels metallurgical properties as 
the metal is heated cooled squeezed and stretched 
by 1983 japans five major plate makers were using controlled 
cooling which helps reduce the need for alloying steel with 
niobium molybdenum and other elements that make the finished 
plates tricky to weld 
its the heart of the technology the pentagon is willing to pay 
american steelmakers to adopt it is a followup technology to 
controlled rolling which the japanese commercialized in the late 
1960s america adopted that in the 1980s mchenry said 
i dont think the industry is being stubborn or hardheaded or 
ignorant by not adopting this technology mchenry said the 
technology is not that attractive from a commercial standpoint 
were not stupid in this country despite what you read said 
marshal mazur manager of government programs for bethlehem steel 
corp a leading plate maker weve been aware of this technology 
for a long time but were a free market economy and we dont 
always have access to all the capital that you need to invest in 
technology 
that situation hasnt always presented itself to our trading 
partners so its real easy for the japanese with easy access to 
capital to go down their wish list and made a decision to 
proceed mazur said 
without government underwriting theres no way you can 
justify putting these units in said anthony de ardo director of 
the basic metals processing research institute at the university of 
pittsburgh 
de ardo however is not a fan of the new japanese technology 
and thinks the pentagon should be looking to us labs for help 
i think the pentagon has been sold a bill of goods on this 
he said but i give them the benefit of the doubt they really 
believe theyre doing something thats correct 
de ardo said japanese steelmakers have shown the benefits of 
accelerated cooling to much of our military and theres no 
question that what theyre saying is true its just that i think 
our steel industry needs many things to benefit the military before 
they get to an accelerated cooling unit 
controlled cooling also called accelerated cooling involves 
computers calculating exactly when to spray water on a hot plate as 
it emerges in its final shape from a rolling mill 
but its not that simple said mchenry who recommended 
highstrength lowalloy steel to the navy after studying the new 
process for a year in japan 
the computer controls when the cooling starts and when the 
cooling stops what the volume of water is what the distribution 
of water is from side to side and what the rate of travel of the 
plate through this shower is he said 
the japanese coupled that technique to direct rolling in which 
molten steel is cast into 8inch thick slabs then rolled directly 
into plate an inch or so thick 
the method eliminates the time and energyconsuming steps of 
cooling the slabs to room temperature to be inspected cleaned of 
surface defects and reheated it is possible only with steel of 
precise and consistent composition itself a benefit of 
computercontrolled furnaces 
together those processes allow for reductions in alloying 
elements including chromium and vanadium which the soviet union 
and south africa control 
japan developed the processes to supply to its busy fabricators 
who produce offshore drilling platforms and transcontinental 
pipelines 
</TEXT>
