<TEXT>
peace in britains twoweek post office strike 
appeared in the balance tuesday night as thousands of workers 
stayed off the job despite mondays settlement of the dispute 
it was still impossible to post a letter in london where mail 
boxes remained sealed 
the post office said work had begun on clearing 150 million 
letters and packages backed up in the system although it expected 
a full return to work by thursday the post office said it could be 
two weeks before service was restored to normal 
as night shifts began it estimated that 20000 of the 100000 
strikers had returned to work it said another 40000 worked during 
the strike 
tuffin general secretary of the union of communication workers 
said agreement was reached monday on the issue of regional pay 
bonuses but the key issue of whether union members would allow 
casual workers to handle the mail backlog had been left to local 
negotiations 
he said the union would back members remaining on strike if they 
could not agree terms on casual labor and overtime with post office 
local managers 
the union said half the countrys 15000 sorting offices were 
still on strike and only six of the 82 major sorting centers were 
working it said staff at glasgow york and hull had voted to stay 
out and similar decisions were expected at other offices 
the strike began as a 24hour walkout on aug 31 against the 
post office desire to pay bonuses to new workers in london and 
southeast england where the cost of living is high and retaining 
workers difficult the union wanted the bonuses paid nationally 
strikes mushroomed sept 1 when the post office tried to bring 
in workers to clear the mail backlog 
tuffin said monday the bonus system had been accepted until a 
new one could be worked out in about six weeks 
</TEXT>
