a federal judge on tuesday accepted most 
of an 875 million jury award to a minnesota woman in her suit 
against gd searle amp co manufacturer of the copper7 
intrauterine device that she said left her sterile 
judge robert renner however lowered the emotional distress 
award given esther kociemba from 1 million to 400000 based on 
state law limiting recovery for intangible losses including 
emotional distress to 400000 
renner said the damage awards for pain and suffering and 
punitive damages would remain 
the jury of five women and three men returned the verdict last 
friday after 10 days of deliberations that began after a 14week 
trial they awarded mrs kociemba 30 of elk river 7 million in 
punitive damages 1 million for emotional distress and 750000 
for pain and disability 
the jury found the birth control device was not properly tested 
and that illinoisbased searle a subsidiary of monsanto co 
failed to warn about risks and intentionally misrepresented the 
copper7 
but the jury also found that searle was not negligent in the 
design or manufacture of the copper7 
renner could have declared that the jurys decision was improper 
and declare a mistrial 
kay bruno a spokeswoman at searle headquarters in skokie ill 
said company attorneys were preparing briefs to be submitted oct 4 
on a motion to dismiss the verdict and request a new trial 
bruno said oral arguments would be presented after attorneys had 
a chance to review the briefs the appeal will take place after 
the posttrial activities and we do anticipate being successful on 
appeal bruno said 
roger brosnahan one of mrs kociembas attorneys said last 
friday the case marked the first time a jury had awarded punitive 
damages against searle for a copper7related illness and also was 
the largest award 
about 500 suits have been filed over the copper7 the most 
widely used iud in the united states before it was withdrawn from 
the us market in january 1986 in the midst of litigation 
mrs kociemba had sought 15 million in punitive damages 15 
million to 2 million in compensatory damages and 300000 in 
compensatory damages for her husband william the jury declined to 
award william kociemba any money for loss of consortium as a direct 
result of his wifes use of the copper7 
some 500 lawsuits have been filed over the copper7 once the 
most widely used iud in the united states before it was withdrawn 
from the us market in january 1986 
searle won 14 of the previous 17 cases to be decided but 
kociemba lawyers have said that none of the previous cases included 
as many documents or deposition testimony as this one 
mrs kociemba used a copper7 for just under 1 years in 1977 
and 1978 she claimed the iud triggered a pelvic infection two 
weeks after insertion and that the infection scarred her fallopian 
tubes leaving her sterile 
